An Introduction to Cascading Style Sheets for Web Developers
CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is the language used to style and
Inline - Applied directly in an HTML tag using the style attribute
In <style> tag - Placed inside an HTML file within the <head> section
External Stylesheet - A separate .css file linked via the <link> tag
Selectors are how you tell CSS which elements to style.
They match parts of the HTML structure and apply styling rules to
- Style elements by tag name, class, ID, attributes, and
- Target elements based on user interaction or document position
- Combine multiple selectors for precise control
- Target HTML elements by their tag name.
- Use a period . followed by the class name.
- Can be applied to multiple elements.
- Use a hash # followed by the ID name.
- Should apply to only one element per page.
- Select elements based on the presence or value of an attribute.
- Add styles based on user interaction or position.
- Use :: to style specific parts of an element.
Apply styles based on device features like screen size.
Check browser compatibility for CSS features
Fun, interactive games for mastering layout
- Keeps HTML clean and focused on content
- Makes it easier to maintain and update styles across pages
- Allows for responsive and adaptive designs on different devices
